# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aws-vpc
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Amazon Virtual Private Cloud aims to provide a service similar to private clouds using technology such as OpenStack or HPE Helion Eucalyptus.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] However, private clouds typically use technology such as OpenShift application hosting and various database systems.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Cloud security experts warn that there can be compliance risks, such as a loss of control or service cancellation in using public resources that do not exist with in-house systems.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] If transaction records are requested from Amazon about a VPC using a national security letter they may not be legally allowed to inform the customer of the breach of the security of their system.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] This would be true even if the actual VPC resources were in another country.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] The API used by AWS is only partly compatible with that of HPE Helion Eucalyptus and is not compatible with other private cloud systems, so migration from AWS may be difficult.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] This has led to warnings of the possibility of a lock-in to a specific technology.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] IP Addressing in Amazon Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) refers to the assignment of IP addresses to the resources within a VPC.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] VPC is Amazon Web Services (AWS) solution for providing isolated network environments for AWS resources.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] IP addresses in a VPC are used for communication between resources within the VPC, as well as for communication between the VPC and the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] There are two types of IP addresses used in a VPC: private IP addresses and public IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Private IP addresses are used for communication between instances within the VPC, while public IP addresses are used for communication between the VPC and the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Amazon VPC provides several options for IP address management, including the use of IPv4 and IPv6 addresses, the automatic assignment of private IP addresses, and the ability to assign static private IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Additionally, Amazon VPC provides the option to associate Elastic IP addresses with instances to ensure persistent public IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] By using Amazon VPC, customers can have full control over the network configuration of their AWS resources, providing increased security and isolation compared to the traditional shared-tenancy model of public cloud computing.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] AWS VPC allows users to connect to the Internet, a user's corporate data center, and other users' VPCs.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Users can connect to the Internet by adding an Internet Gateway to their VPC, which assigns the VPC a public IPv4 Address.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Users can connect to a data center by setting up a hardware virtual private network connection between the data center and the VPC.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Users are also able to route traffic from one VPC to another VPC using private IP addresses and can communicate as if they were on the same network.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] Peering can be achieved by connecting a route between two VPCs on the same account or two VPCs on different accounts in the same region.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] VPC peering is a one-to-one connection, but users can connect to more than one VPC at a time.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] To achieve a one-to-many connection between VPCs, you can deploy a transit gateway (TGW).
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] In addition, you can connect your VPCs to your on-premise systems by employing the transit gateway.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] AWS VPC's security is two-fold: firstly, AWS VPC uses security groups as a firewall to control traffic at the instance level, while it also uses network access control lists as a firewall to control traffic at the subnet level.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] As another measure of privacy, AWS VPC provides users with the ability to create "dedicated instances" on hardware, physically isolating the dedicated instances from non-dedicated instances and instances owned by other accounts.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] AWS VPC is free, with users only paying for the consumption of EC2 resources.
[src:aws-vpc/amazon-virtual-private-cloud] However, if users choose to access VPC via a Virtual Private Network (VPN), there is a charge.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] IP addresses are described as consisting of two groups of bits in the address: the most significant bits are the network prefix, which identifies a whole network or subnet, and the least significant set forms the *host identifier*, which specifies a particular interface of a host on that network.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] This division is used as the basis of traffic routing between IP networks and for address allocation policies.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Whereas classful network design for IPv4 sized the network prefix as one or more eight-bit groups, resulting in the blocks of Class A, B, or C addresses, under CIDR address space, is allocated to Internet service providers (ISPs) and end users on any address-bit boundary.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In IPv6, however, the interface identifier has a fixed size of 64 bits by convention, and smaller subnets are never allocated to end users.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is based on **variable-length subnet masking** (**VLSM**), in which network prefixes have variable length as opposed to the fixed-length prefixing of the previous classful network design.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The main benefit of this is that it grants finer control of the sizes of subnets allocated to organizations, hence slowing the exhaustion of IPv4 addresses from the allocation of larger subnets than needed.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR gave rise to a new way of writing IP addresses known as CIDR notation, in which an IP address is followed by a suffix indicating the number of bits of the prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Blocks of addresses having contiguous prefixes may be aggregated as supernets, reducing the number of entries in the global routing table.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Each IP address consists of a network prefix followed by a host identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In the classful network architecture of IPv4, the three most significant bits of the 32-bit IP address defined the size of the network prefix for unicast networking, and determined the network class A, B, or C.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The advantage of this system is that the network prefix can be determined for any IP address without any further information.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The disadvantage is that networks were usually too big or too small for most organizations to use, because only three sizes were available.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The smallest allocation and routing block contained 28 = 256 addresses, larger than necessary for personal or department networks, but too small for most enterprises.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The next larger block contained 216 = 65536 addresses, too large to be used efficiently even by large organizations.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] But for network users who needed more than 65536 addresses, the only other size (224) provided far too many, more than 16 million.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] This led to inefficiencies in address use as well as inefficiencies in routing, because it required a large number of allocated class-C networks with individual route announcements, being geographically dispersed with little opportunity for route aggregation.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Within a decade after the invention of the Domain Name System (DNS), the classful network method was found not scalable.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] This led to the development of subnetting and CIDR.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The formerly meaningful class distinctions based on the most-significant address bits were abandoned and the new system was described as "classless", in contrast to the old system, which became known as "classful".
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Routing protocols were revised to carry not just IP addresses, but also their subnet masks.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Implementing CIDR required every host and router on the Internet to be reprogrammed in small ways—no small feat at a time when the Internet was entering a period of rapid growth.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In 1993, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a new set of standards, RFC 1518 and RFC 1519, to define this new principle for allocating IP address blocks and routing IPv4 packets.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] An updated version, RFC 4632, was published in 2006.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] After a period of experimentation with various alternatives, Classless Inter-Domain Routing was based on variable-length subnet masking (VLSM), which allows each network to be divided into subnetworks of various power-of-two sizes, so that each subnetwork can be sized appropriately for local needs.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Variable-length subnet masks were mentioned as one alternative in RFC 950.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Techniques for grouping addresses for common operations were based on the concept of cluster addressing, first proposed by Carl-Herbert Rokitansky.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The address may denote a specific interface address (including a host identifier, such as *10.0.0.1/8*), or it may be the beginning address of an entire network (using a host identifier of 0, as in *10.0.0.0/8* or its equivalent *10/8*).
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR notation can even be used with no IP address at all, e.g. when referring to a */24* as a generic description of an IPv4 network that has a 24-bit prefix and 8-bit host numbers.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In IPv4, CIDR notation came into wide use only after the implementation of the method, which was documented using dotted-decimal subnet mask specification after the slash, for example, *192.24.12.0/255.255.252.0*.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Describing the network prefix width as a single number (*192.24.12.0/22*) was easier for network administrators to conceptualize and to calculate.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] It became gradually incorporated into later standards documents and into network configuration interfaces.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The number of addresses of a network may be calculated as 2address length − prefix length, where "address length" is 128 for IPv6 and 32 for IPv4.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, in IPv4, the prefix length */29* gives: 232−29 = 23 = 8 addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] A subnet mask is a bitmask that encodes the prefix length associated with an IPv4 address or network in quad-dotted notation: 32 bits, starting with a number of ones equal to the prefix length, ending with zeros, and encoded in four-part dotted-decimal format: *255.255.255.0*.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] A subnet mask encodes the same information as a prefix length but predates the advent of CIDR.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In CIDR notation, the prefix bits are always contiguous.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Subnet masks were allowed by RFC 950 to specify non-contiguous bits until RFC 4632 stated that the mask must consist of only contiguous ones, if any, in the more significant bits and contiguous zeroes, if any, in the less significant bits.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Given this constraint, a subnet mask and CIDR notation serve exactly the same function.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is principally a bitwise, prefix-based standard for the representation of IP addresses and their routing properties.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] It facilitates routing by allowing blocks of addresses to be grouped into single routing table entries.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] These groups, commonly called CIDR blocks, share an initial sequence of bits in the binary representation of their IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] IPv4 CIDR blocks are identified using a syntax similar to that of IPv4 addresses: a dotted-decimal address, followed by a slash, then a number from 0 to 32, i.e., *a.b.c.d/n*.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The dotted-decimal portion is the IPv4 address.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The number following the slash is the prefix length, the number of shared initial bits, counting from the most-significant bit of the address.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] When emphasizing only the size of a network, the address portion of the notation is usually omitted.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Thus, a /20 block is a CIDR block with an unspecified 20-bit prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] An IP address is part of a CIDR block and is said to match the CIDR prefix if the initial n bits of the address and the CIDR prefix are the same.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] An IPv4 address is 32 bits so an n-bit CIDR prefix leaves 32−n bits unmatched, meaning that 232−n IPv4 addresses match a given n-bit CIDR prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Shorter CIDR prefixes match more addresses, while longer prefixes match fewer.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In the case of overlaid CIDR blocks, an address can match multiple CIDR prefixes of different lengths.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR is also used for IPv6 addresses and the syntax semantic is identical.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The prefix length can range from 0 to 128, due to the larger number of bits in the address.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] However, by convention, a subnet on broadcast MAC layer networks always has 64-bit host identifiers.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Larger prefixes (/127) are only used on some point-to-point links between routers, for security and policy reasons.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA) issues to regional Internet registries (RIRs) large, short-prefix CIDR blocks.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] However, a */8* (with over sixteen million addresses) is the largest block IANA will allocate.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, *62.0.0.0/8* is administered by RIPE NCC, the European RIR.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The RIRs, each responsible for a single, large geographic area, such as Europe or North America, subdivide these blocks and allocate subnets to local Internet registries (LIRs).
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Similar subdividing may be repeated several times at lower levels of delegation.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] End-user networks receive subnets sized according to their projected short-term need.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Networks served by a single ISP are encouraged by IETF recommendations to obtain IP address space directly from their ISP.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Networks served by multiple ISPs, on the other hand, may obtain provider-independent address space directly from the appropriate RIR.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, in the late 1990s, the IP address *208.130.29.33* (since reassigned) was used by www.freesoft.org.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] An analysis of this address identified three CIDR prefixes.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] *208.128.0.0/11*, a large CIDR block containing over 2 million addresses, had been assigned by ARIN (the North American RIR) to MCI.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Automation Research Systems (ARS), a Virginia VAR, leased an Internet connection from MCI and was assigned the *208.130.28.0/22* block, capable of addressing just over 1000 devices.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] ARS used a */24* block for its publicly accessible servers, of which *208.130.29.33* was one.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] All of these CIDR prefixes would be used at different locations in the network.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Outside MCI's network, the *208.128.0.0/11* prefix would be used to direct to MCI traffic bound not only for *208.130.29.33*, but also for any of the roughly two million IP addresses with the same initial 11 bits.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Within MCI's network, *208.130.28.0/22* would become visible, directing traffic to the leased line serving ARS.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Only within the ARS corporate network would the *208.130.29.0/24* prefix have been used.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In routed subnets larger than */31* or */32*, the number of available host addresses is usually reduced by two, namely the largest address, which is reserved as the broadcast address, and the smallest address, which identifies the network itself and is reserved solely for this purpose.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] In such usage, a */31* network, with one binary digit in the host identifier, is unusable, as such a subnet would provide no available host addresses after this reduction.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] RFC 3021 creates an exception to the "host all ones" and "host all zeros" rules to make */31* networks usable for point-to-point links.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] */32* addresses (single-host network) must be accessed by explicit routing rules, as there is no address available for a gateway.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The large address size of IPv6 permitted worldwide route summarization and guaranteed sufficient address pools at each site.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The standard subnet size for IPv6 networks is a */64* block, which is required for the operation of stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] This IPv6 subnetting reference lists the sizes for IPv6 subnetworks.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Different types of network links may require different subnet sizes.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] The subnet mask separates the bits of the network identifier prefix from the bits of the interface identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Selecting a smaller prefix size results in fewer number of networks covered, but with more addresses within each network.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Topologically, the set of subnets described by CIDR represents a cover of the corresponding address space.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] For a fixed n , the set of all $X/n$ subnets constitutes a partition, that is, a cover of non-overlapping sets.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Increasing n yields finer and finer subpartitions.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] Thus, two subnets $X/n$ and $Y/m$ are either disjoint or one is a subnet of the other.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] CIDR provides fine-grained routing prefix aggregation.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] For example, if the first 20 bits of their network prefixes match, sixteen contiguous */24* networks can be aggregated and advertised to a larger network as a single */20* routing table entry.
[src:aws-vpc/classless-inter-domain-routing] This reduces the number of routes that have to be advertised.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] As network address translation modifies the IP address information in packets, NAT implementations may vary in their specific behavior in various addressing cases and their effect on network traffic.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Vendors of equipment containing NAT implementations do not commonly document the specifics of NAT behavior.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4) uses 32-bit addresses, capable of uniquely addressing about 4.3 billion devices on the network.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] By 1992, it became evident that this would not be enough.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The 1994 RFC 1631 describes NAT as a "short-term solution" to the two most compelling problems facing the Internet Protocol at that time: IP address depletion and scaling in routing.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The technique also became known as **IP masquerading**, which suggests a technique that hides an entire IP address space, usually consisting of private IP addresses, behind a single IP address in another, usually public address space.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Because of the popularity of this technique to conserve IPv4 address space, the term *NAT* became virtually synonymous with IP masquerading.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In 1996, port-address translation (PAT) was introduced, which expanded the translation of addresses to include port numbers.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The simplest type of NAT provides a one-to-one translation of IP addresses (RFC 1631).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 refers to this type of NAT as *basic NAT*, also called a *one-to-one NAT*.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In this type of NAT, only the IP addresses, IP header checksum, and any higher-level checksums that include the IP address are changed.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Basic NAT can be used to interconnect two IP networks with incompatible addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Most network address translators map multiple private hosts to one publicly exposed IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In a typical configuration, a local network uses one of the designated *private* IP address subnets (RFC 1918).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The network has a router having network interfaces on both the private and the public networks.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The public address is typically assigned by an Internet service provider.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] As traffic passes from the private network to the Internet, NAT translates the source address in each packet from a private address to the router's public address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The NAT facility tracks each active connection.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] When the router receives inbound traffic from the Internet, it uses the connection tracking data obtained during the outbound phase to determine to which private address it should forward the reply.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Packets passing from the private network to the public network will have their source address modified, while packets passing from the public network back to the private network will have their destination address modified.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] To avoid ambiguity in how replies are translated, further modifications to the packets are required.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The vast bulk of Internet traffic uses Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) or User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For these protocols, the port numbers are changed so that the combination of IP address (within the IP header) and port number (within the Transport Layer header) on the returned packet can be unambiguously mapped to the corresponding private network destination.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] RFC 2663 uses the term **network address and port translation** (**NAPT**) for this type of NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Other names include **port address translation** (**PAT**), *IP masquerading*, *NAT overload*, and *many-to-one NAT*.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This is the most common type of NAT and has become synonymous with the term *NAT* in common usage.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This method allows communication through the router only when the conversation originates in the private network, since the initial originating transmission establishes the required information in the translation tables.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Thus, a web browser within the private network is able to browse websites that are outside the network, whereas web browsers outside the network are unable to browse a website hosted within.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Protocols not based on TCP and UDP require other translation techniques.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The primary benefit of one-to-many NAT is mitigation of IPv4 address exhaustion by allowing entire networks to be connected to the Internet using a single public IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Network address and port translation may be implemented in several ways.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Some applications that use IP address information may need to determine the external address of a network address translator.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This is the address that its communication peers in the external network detect.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Furthermore, it may be necessary to examine and categorize the type of mapping in use, for example, when it is desired to set up a direct communication path between two clients, both of which are behind separate NAT gateways.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For this purpose, RFC 3489 specified the protocol *Simple Traversal of UDP over NATs* (STUN) in 2003.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] It classified NAT implementations as *full-cone NAT*, *(address) restricted-cone NAT*, *port-restricted cone NAT* or *symmetric NAT*, and proposed a methodology for testing a device accordingly.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] However, these procedures have since been deprecated from standards status, as the methods are inadequate to correctly assess many devices.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] RFC 5389 standardized new methods in 2008 and the acronym *STUN* since represents the new title of the specification: *Session Traversal Utilities for NAT*.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] As many NAT implementations combine multiple types, it is better to refer to specific individual NAT behavior instead of using the Cone/Symmetric terminology.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 attempts to alleviate confusion by introducing standardized terminology for observed behaviors.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For the first bullet in each row of the above table, the RFC would characterize Full-Cone, Restricted-Cone, and Port-Restricted-Cone NATs as having an *Endpoint-Independent Mapping*, whereas it would characterize a Symmetric NAT as having an *Address- and Port-Dependent Mapping*.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Other classifications of NAT behavior mentioned in the RFC include whether they preserve ports, when and how mappings are refreshed, whether external mappings can be used by internal hosts (i.e., its hairpinning behavior), and the level of determinism NATs exhibit when applying all these rules.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Specifically, most NATs combine *symmetric NAT* for outgoing connections with *static port mapping*, where incoming packets addressed to the external address and port are redirected to a specific internal address and port.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] RFC 4787 distinguishes between NAT mapping and NAT filtering.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Section 4.1 of the RFC covers NAT mapping and specifies the translation of an external IP address and port number into an internal IP address and port number.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Section 5 of the RFC covers NAT filtering and describes the criteria used by the NAT to filter packets originating from specific external endpoints.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The options are endpoint-independent filtering, address-dependent filtering and address- and port-dependent filtering.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Endpoint-independent filtering is recommended where maximum application transparency is required while address-dependent filtering is recommended where more stringent filtering behavior is most important.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Some NAT devices are not compliant with RFC 4787 as they treat NAT mapping and filtering in the same way, so that their configuration option for changing the NAT filtering method also changes the NAT mapping method (e.g., Netgate TNSR Archived 2024-01-30 at the Wayback Machine).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] NAT traversal problems arise when peers behind different NATs try to communicate.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] One way to solve this problem is to use port forwarding.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Another way is to use various NAT traversal techniques.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The most popular technique for TCP NAT traversal is TCP hole punching.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] TCP hole punching requires the NAT to follow the *port preservation* design for TCP.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For a given outgoing TCP communication, the same port numbers are used on both sides of the NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] NAT port preservation for outgoing TCP connections is crucial for TCP NAT traversal because, under TCP, one port can only be used for one communication at a time.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Programs that bind distinct TCP sockets to ephemeral ports for each TCP communication make NAT port prediction impossible for TCP.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] On the other hand, for UDP, NATs do not need port preservation.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Indeed, multiple UDP communications (each with a distinct endpoint) can occur on the same source port, and applications usually reuse the same UDP socket to send packets to distinct hosts.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This makes port prediction straightforward, as it is the same source port for each packet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Furthermore, port preservation in NAT for TCP allows P2P protocols to offer less complexity and less latency because there is no need to use a third party (like STUN) to discover the NAT port since the application itself already knows the NAT port.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Every TCP and UDP packet contains a source port number and a destination port number.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Each of those packets is encapsulated in an IP packet, whose IP header contains a source IP address and a destination IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The IP address/protocol/port number triple defines an association with a network socket.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For publicly accessible services such as web and mail servers, the port number is important.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For example, port 443 connects through a socket to the web server software and port 465 to a mail server's SMTP daemon.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The IP address of a public server is also important, similar in global uniqueness to a postal address or telephone number.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Both the IP address and port number must be correctly known by all hosts wishing to communicate successfully.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Private IP addresses as described in RFC 1918, are usable only on private networks not directly connected to the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Ports are endpoints of communication unique to that host, so a connection through the NAT device is maintained by the combined mapping of port and IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] A private address on the inside of the NAT is mapped to an external public address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Port address translation (PAT) resolves conflicts that arise when multiple hosts happen to use the same source port number to establish different external connections at the same time.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] With NAT, all communications sent to external hosts actually contain the *external* IP address and port information of the NAT device instead of internal host IP addresses or port numbers.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] NAT only translates IP addresses and ports of its internal hosts, hiding the true endpoint of an internal host on a private network.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] When a computer on the private (internal) network sends an IP packet to the external network, the NAT device replaces the internal source IP address in the packet header with the external IP address of the NAT device.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] PAT may then assign the connection a port number from a pool of available ports, inserting this port number in the source port field.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The packet is then forwarded to the external network.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The NAT device then makes an entry in a translation table containing the internal IP address, original source port, and the translated source port.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Subsequent packets from the same internal source IP address and port number are translated to the same external source IP address and port number.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The computer receiving a packet that has undergone NAT establishes a connection to the port and IP address specified in the altered packet, oblivious to the fact that the supplied address is being translated.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Upon receiving a packet from the external network, the NAT device searches the translation table based on the destination port in the packet header.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If a match is found, the destination IP address and port number are replaced with the values found in the table and the packet is forwarded to the inside network.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Otherwise, if the destination port number of the incoming packet is not found in the translation table, the packet is dropped or rejected because the PAT device doesn't know where to send it.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Network address translation can be used to mitigate IP address overlap.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Address overlap occurs when hosts in different networks with the same IP address space try to reach the same destination host.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The destination host experiences traffic apparently arriving from the same network, and intermediate routers have no way to determine where reply traffic should be sent to.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The solution is either renumbering to eliminate overlap or network address translation.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] forward client requests to a set of server computers to manage the workload of each server.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Network address translation may be used to map a representative IP address of the server cluster to specific hosts that service the request.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] IEEE Reverse Address and Port Translation (RAPT or RAT) allows a host whose real IP address changes from time to time to remain reachable as a server via a fixed home IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Cisco's RAPT implementation is PAT or NAT overloading and maps multiple private IP addresses to a single public IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Multiple addresses can be mapped to a single address because each private address is tracked by a port number.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] PAT uses unique source port numbers on the inside global IP address to distinguish between translations.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] PAT attempts to preserve the original source port.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If this source port is already used, PAT assigns the first available port number starting from the beginning of the appropriate port group 0–511, 512–1023, or 1024–65535.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] When there are no more ports available and there is more than one external IP address configured, PAT moves to the next IP address to try to allocate the original source port again.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This process continues until it runs out of available ports and external IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Mapping of Address and Port is a Cisco proposal that combines Address plus Port translation with tunneling of the IPv4 packets over an ISP provider's internal IPv6 network.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In effect, it is an (almost) stateless alternative to carrier-grade NAT and DS-Lite that pushes the IPv4 address/port translation function (and the maintenance of NAT state) entirely into the existing customer premises equipment NAT implementation.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Thus avoiding the NAT444 and statefulness problems of carrier-grade NAT, and also provides a transition mechanism for the deployment of native IPv6 at the same time with very little added complexity.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Hosts behind NAT-enabled routers do not have end-to-end connectivity and cannot participate in some internet protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Services that require the initiation of TCP connections from the outside network, or that use stateless protocols such as those using UDP, can be disrupted.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Unless the NAT router makes a specific effort to support such protocols, incoming packets cannot reach their destination.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Some protocols can accommodate one instance of NAT between participating hosts ("passive mode" FTP, for example), sometimes with the assistance of an application-level gateway (see § Applications affected by NAT), but fail when both systems are separated from the internet by NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The use of NAT also complicates tunneling protocols such as IPsec because NAT modifies values in the headers, which interfere with the integrity checks done by IPsec and other tunneling protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] End-to-end connectivity has been a core principle of the Internet, supported, for example, by the Internet Architecture Board.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Current Internet architectural documents observe that NAT is a violation of the end-to-end principle, but that NAT does have a valid role in careful design.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] There is considerably more concern with the use of IPv6 NAT, and many IPv6 architects believe IPv6 was intended to remove the need for NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] An implementation that only tracks ports can be quickly depleted by internal applications that use multiple simultaneous connections, such as an HTTP request for a web page with many embedded objects.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This problem can be mitigated by tracking the destination IP address in addition to the port, thus sharing a single local port with many remote hosts.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This additional tracking increases implementation complexity and computing resources at the translation device.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Because the internal addresses are all disguised behind one publicly accessible address, it is impossible for external hosts to directly initiate a connection to a particular internal host.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Applications such as VOIP, videoconferencing, and other peer-to-peer applications must use NAT traversal techniques to function.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Pure NAT, operating on IP alone, may or may not correctly parse protocols with payloads containing information about IP, such as ICMP.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This depends on whether the payload is interpreted by a host on the *inside* or *outside* of the translation.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Basic protocols such as TCP and UDP cannot function properly unless NAT takes action beyond the network layer.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] IP packets have a checksum in each packet header, which provides error detection only for the header.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] IP datagrams may become fragmented and it is necessary for a NAT to reassemble these fragments to allow correct recalculation of higher-level checksums and correct tracking of which packets belong to which connection.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] TCP and UDP have a checksum that covers all the data they carry, as well as the TCP or UDP header, plus a *pseudo-header* that contains the source and destination IP addresses of the packet carrying the TCP or UDP header.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For an originating NAT to pass TCP or UDP successfully, it must recompute the TCP or UDP header checksum based on the translated IP addresses, not the original ones, and put that checksum into the TCP or UDP header of the first packet of the fragmented set of packets.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Alternatively, the originating host may perform path MTU Discovery to determine the packet size that can be transmitted without fragmentation and then set the *don't fragment* (DF) bit in the appropriate packet header field.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This is only a one-way solution, because the responding host can send packets of any size, which may be fragmented before reaching the NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Destination network address translation (DNAT) is a technique for transparently changing the destination IP address of a routed packet and performing the inverse function for any replies.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Any router situated between two endpoints can perform this transformation of the packet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] DNAT is commonly used to publish a service located in a private network on a publicly accessible IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This use of DNAT is also called port forwarding, or DMZ when used on an entire server, which becomes exposed to the WAN, becoming analogous to an undefended military demilitarized zone (DMZ).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Secure network address translation (SNAT) is part of Microsoft's Internet Security and Acceleration Server and is an extension to the NAT driver built into Microsoft Windows Server.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] It provides connection tracking and filtering for the additional network connections needed for the FTP, ICMP, H.323, and PPTP protocols as well as the ability to configure a transparent HTTP proxy server.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Dynamic NAT, just like static NAT, is not common in smaller networks but is found within larger corporations with complex networks.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Where static NAT provides a one-to-one internal to public static IP address mapping, dynamic NAT uses a *group* of public IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If a packet is sent to *203.0.113.1* by a computer at *192.168.1.100*, the packet would normally be routed to the default gateway (the router).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] A router with the NAT loopback feature detects that *203.0.113.1* is the address of its WAN interface, and treats the packet as if coming from that interface.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] It determines the destination for that packet, based on DNAT (port forwarding) rules for the destination.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If the data were sent to port 80 and a DNAT rule exists for port 80 directed to *192.168.1.2*, then the host at that address receives the packet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If no applicable DNAT rule is available, the router drops the packet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] An ICMP Destination Unreachable reply may be sent.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If any DNAT rules were present, address translation is still in effect; the router still rewrites the source IP address in the packet.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Because the source address is part of the same broadcast domain as the server, it will respond with a packet destined directly to the local computer on layer 2, without involving the router.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] As the local computer did not expect any traffic from *192.168.1.2* (the local address of the server), but from *203.0.113.1*, the address that it actually intended to connect to, it will silently drop the response.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] To enable two-way communication using the external address between these hosts, an SNAT rule must be configured.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Such a rule specifies that traffic received from the local network and destined to the server (to its local address, after rewriting) should have its source address rewritten to an address of the router.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This way, the response of the server will be sent to the router, which is then able to apply the reverse SNAT and DNAT transformations and send the expected response back to the local computer.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Thus, two-way communication is possible between hosts inside the LAN network via the public IP address, as long as appropriate NAT rules are set up.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Network address translation is not commonly used in IPv6 because one of the design goals of IPv6 is to restore end-to-end network connectivity.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 obviates the need to conserve addresses and every device can be given a unique globally routable address.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Use of unique local addresses in combination with network prefix translation can achieve results similar to NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The large addressing space of IPv6 can still be defeated, depending on the actual prefix length given by the carrier.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] It is not uncommon to be handed a /64 prefix – the smallest recommended subnet – for an entire home network, requiring a variety of techniques to be used to manually subdivide the range for all devices to remain reachable.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In such cases, it may be required to use full network address and port translation (NAPT) on IPv6, usually referred to as NAT66, where an IPv6 ULA prefix is masqueraded down to a single IPv6 global unique address (GUA).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The APNIC blog outlines a case where the author was only provided a single address (/128).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Some application layer protocols, such as File Transfer Protocol (FTP) and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), send explicit network addresses within their application data.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] File Transfer Protocol in active mode, for example, uses separate connections for control traffic (commands) and for data traffic (file contents).
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] When requesting a file transfer, the host making the request identifies the corresponding data connection by its network layer and transport layer addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If the host making the request lies behind a simple NAT firewall, the translation of the IP address or TCP port number makes the information received by the server invalid.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] SIP commonly controls voice over IP calls, and suffer the same problem.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] SIP and its accompanying Session Description Protocol may use multiple ports to set up a connection and transmit a voice stream via Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] IP addresses and port numbers are encoded in the payload data and must be known before the traversal of NATs.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Without special techniques, such as STUN, NAT behavior is unpredictable and communications may fail.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Application Layer Gateway (ALG) software or hardware may correct these problems.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] An ALG software module running on a NAT firewall device updates any payload data made invalid by address translation.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] ALGs need to understand the higher-layer protocol that they need to fix, and so each protocol with this problem requires a separate ALG.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] For example, on many Linux systems, there are kernel modules called *connection trackers* that serve to implement ALGs.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] However, ALG cannot work if the protocol data is encrypted.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Another possible solution to this problem is to use NAT traversal techniques using protocols such as STUN or Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE), or proprietary approaches in a session border controller.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] NAT traversal is possible in both TCP- and UDP-based applications, but the UDP-based technique is simpler, more widely understood, and more compatible with legacy NATs.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In either case, the high-level protocol must be designed with NAT traversal in mind, and it does not work reliably across symmetric NATs or other poorly behaved legacy NATs.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Other possibilities are Port Control Protocol (PCP), NAT Port Mapping Protocol (NAT-PMP), or Internet Gateway Device Protocol but these require the NAT device to implement that protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Most client–server protocols (FTP being the main exception), however, do not send layer 3 contact information and do not require any special treatment by NATs.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In fact, avoiding NAT complications is practically a requirement when designing new higher-layer protocols today.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] NATs can also cause problems where IPsec encryption is applied and in cases where multiple devices, such as SIP phones are located behind a NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Phones that encrypt their signaling with IPsec encapsulate the port information within an encrypted packet, meaning that NAT devices cannot access and translate the port.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] In these cases, the NAT devices revert to simple NAT operations.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] This means that all traffic returning to the NAT is mapped onto one client, causing service to more than one client behind the NAT to fail.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE) is a NAT traversal technique that does not rely on ALG support.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The DNS protocol vulnerability announced by Dan Kaminsky on July 8, 2008, is indirectly affected by NAT port mapping.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] To avoid DNS cache poisoning, it is highly desirable not to translate UDP source port numbers of outgoing DNS requests from a DNS server behind a firewall that implements NAT.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] The recommended workaround for the DNS vulnerability is to make all caching DNS servers use randomized UDP source ports.
[src:aws-vpc/network-address-translation] If the NAT function de-randomizes the UDP source ports, the DNS server becomes vulnerable.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] A **subnet**, or **subnetwork**, is a logical subdivision of an IP network.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The practice of dividing a network into two or more networks is called **subnetting**.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Computers that belong to the same subnet are addressed with an identical group of most-significant bits of their IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This results in the logical division of an IP address into two fields: the *network number* or *routing prefix*, and the *rest field* or *host identifier*.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The *rest field* is an identifier for a specific host or network interface.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The *routing prefix* may be expressed as the first address of a network, written in Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR) notation, followed by a slash character (*/*), and ending with the bit-length of the prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For example, *198.51.100.0/24* is the prefix of the Internet Protocol version 4 network starting at the given address, having 24 bits allocated for the network prefix, and the remaining 8 bits reserved for host addressing.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The IPv6 address specification *2001:db8::/32* is a large address block with 296 addresses, having a 32-bit routing prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For IPv4, a network may also be characterized by its **subnet mask** or **netmask**, which is the bitmask that, when applied by a bitwise AND operation to any IP address in the network, yields the routing prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Subnet masks are also expressed in dot-decimal notation like an IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Traffic is exchanged between subnets through routers when the routing prefixes of the source address and the destination address differ.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] A router serves as a logical or physical boundary between the subnets.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The benefits of subnetting an existing network vary with each deployment scenario.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In the address allocation architecture of the Internet, using CIDR, and in large organizations, efficient allocation of address space is necessary.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Subnetting may also enhance routing efficiency or have advantages in network management when subnets are administratively controlled by different entities in a larger organization.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Subnets may be arranged logically in a hierarchical architecture, partitioning an organization's network address space into a tree-like routing structure or other structures, such as meshes.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Computers participating in an IP network have at least one network address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Usually, this address is unique to each device and can either be configured automatically by a network service with the Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol (DHCP), manually by an administrator, or automatically by the operating system with stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] An address fulfills the functions of identifying the host and locating it on the network in destination routing.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The most common network addressing architecture is Internet Protocol version 4 (IPv4), but its successor, IPv6, has been increasingly deployed since approximately 2006.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In both architectures, an IP address is divided into two logical parts, the *network prefix* and the *host identifier*.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] All hosts on a subnet have the same network prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This prefix occupies the most significant bits of the address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The number of bits allocated within a network to the prefix may vary between subnets, depending on the network architecture.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The host identifier is a unique local identification and is either a host number on the local network or an interface identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Routers constitute logical or physical borders between the subnets and manage traffic between them.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Each subnet is served by a designated default router but may consist internally of multiple physical Ethernet segments interconnected by network switches.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The routing prefix of an address is identified by the *subnet mask*, written in the same form used for IP addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For example, the subnet mask for a routing prefix that is composed of the most-significant 24 bits of an IPv4 address is written as *255.255.255.0*.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The modern standard form of specification of the network prefix is CIDR notation, used for both IPv4 and IPv6.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] It counts the number of bits in the prefix and appends that number to the address after a *slash* (/) character separator.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This notation was introduced with Classless Inter-Domain Routing (CIDR).
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In IPv6 this is the only standards-based form to denote network or routing prefixes.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In classful networking in IPv4, before the introduction of CIDR, the network prefix could be directly obtained from the IP address, based on its highest-order bit sequence.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This determined the class (A, B, C) of the address and, therefore, the subnet mask.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Since the introduction of CIDR, however, the assignment of an IP address to a network interface requires two parameters, the address and a subnet mask.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Given an IPv4 source address, its associated subnet mask, and the destination address, a router can determine whether the destination is on a locally connected network or a remote network.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The subnet mask of the destination is not needed, and is generally not known to a router.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For IPv6, however, on-link determination is different in detail and requires the Neighbor Discovery Protocol (NDP).
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] IPv6 address assignment to an interface carries no requirement of a matching on-link prefix and vice versa, with the exception of link-local addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Since each locally connected subnet must be represented by a separate entry in the routing tables of each connected router, subnetting increases routing complexity.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] However, by careful design of the network, routes to collections of more distant subnets within the branches of a tree hierarchy can be aggregated into a supernetwork and represented by single routes.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] An IPv4 subnet mask consists of 32 bits; it is a sequence of ones (*1*) followed by a block of zeros (*0*).
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The ones indicate bits in the address used for the network prefix, and the trailing block of zeros designates that part as being the host identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The following example shows the separation of the network prefix and the host identifier from an address (*192.0.2.130*) and its associated */24* subnet mask (*255.255.255.0*).
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The operation is visualized in a table using binary address formats.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The result of the bitwise AND operation of IP address and the subnet mask is the network prefix *192.0.2.0*.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The host part, which is *130*, is derived by the bitwise AND operation of the address and the ones' complement of the subnet mask.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Subnetting is the process of designating some high-order bits from the host part as part of the network prefix and adjusting the subnet mask appropriately.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This divides a network into smaller subnets.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The following diagram modifies the above example by moving 2 bits from the host part to the network prefix to form four smaller subnets, each one quarter of the previous size.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] IPv4 uses specially designated address formats to facilitate recognition of special address functionality.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The first and the last subnets obtained by subnetting a larger network have traditionally had a special designation and, early on, special usage implications.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In addition, IPv4 uses the *all ones* host address, i.e., the last address within a network, for broadcast transmission to all hosts on the link.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The first subnet obtained from subnetting a larger network has all bits in the subnet bit group set to zero.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The last subnet obtained from subnetting a larger network has all bits in the subnet bit group set to one.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] It is therefore called the *all-ones subnet*.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The IETF originally discouraged the production use of these two subnets.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] When the prefix length is not available, the larger network and the first subnet have the same address, which may lead to confusion.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Similar confusion is possible with the broadcast address at the end of the last subnet.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Therefore, reserving the subnet values consisting of all zeros and all ones on the public Internet was recommended, reducing the number of available subnets by two for each subnetting.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This inefficiency was removed, and the practice was declared obsolete in 1995, and is only relevant when dealing with legacy equipment.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Although the all-zeros and the all-ones host values are reserved for the network address of the subnet and its broadcast address, respectively, in systems using CIDR, all subnets are available in a subdivided network.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For example, a */24* network can be divided into sixteen usable */28* networks.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The number of subnets available and the number of possible hosts in a network may be readily calculated.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] For instance, the *192.168.5.0/24* network may be subdivided into the following four */26* subnets.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The highlighted two address bits become part of the network number in this process.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The remaining bits after the subnet bits are used for addressing hosts within the subnet.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In the above example, the subnet mask consists of 26 bits, making it 255.255.255.192, leaving 6 bits for the host identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] This allows for 62 host combinations (26−2).
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In general, the number of available hosts on a subnet is 2*h*−2, where *h* is the number of bits used for the host portion of the address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The number of available subnets is 2*n*, where *n* is the number of bits used for the network portion of the address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] There is an exception to this rule for 31-bit subnet masks,, which means the host identifier is only one bit long for two permissible addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In such networks, usually point-to-point links, only two hosts (the endpoints) may be connected, and a specification of network and broadcast addresses is not necessary.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The design of the IPv6 address space differs significantly from IPv4.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The primary reason for subnetting in IPv4 is to improve efficiency in the utilization of the relatively small address space available, particularly to enterprises.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] No such limitations exist in IPv6, as the large address space available, even to end-users, is not a limiting factor.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] As in IPv4, subnetting in IPv6 is based on the concepts of variable-length subnet masking (VLSM) and the Classless Inter-Domain Routing methodology.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] It is used to route traffic between the global allocation spaces and within customer networks between subnets and the Internet at large.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] A compliant IPv6 subnet always uses addresses with 64 bits in the host identifier.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Given the address size of 128 bits, it therefore has a /64 routing prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Although it is technically possible to use smaller subnets, they are impractical for local area networks based on Ethernet technology, because 64 bits are required for stateless address autoconfiguration.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The Internet Engineering Task Force recommends the use of */127* subnets for point-to-point links, which have only two hosts.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] IPv6 does not implement special address formats for broadcast traffic or network numbers, and thus all addresses in a subnet are acceptable for host addressing.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The all-zeroes address is reserved as the subnet-router anycast address.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The subnet router anycast address is the lowest address in the subnet, so it looks like the “network address”.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] If a router has multiple subnets on the same link, then it has multiple subnet router anycast addresses on that link.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] The first and last address in any network or subnet is not allowed to be assigned to any individual host.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] In the past, the recommended allocation for an IPv6 customer site was an address space with a 48-bit (*/48*) prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] However, this recommendation was revised to encourage smaller blocks, for example, using 56-bit prefixes.
[src:aws-vpc/subnetwork] Another common allocation size for residential customer networks has a 64-bit prefix.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] A **virtual private cloud** (**VPC**) is an on-demand configurable pool of shared resources allocated within a *public cloud* environment, providing a certain level of isolation between the different organizations (denoted as *users* hereafter) using the resources.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] The isolation between one VPC user and all other users of the same cloud (other VPC users as well as other public cloud users) is achieved normally through allocation of a private IP subnet and a virtual communication construct (such as a VLAN or a set of encrypted communication channels) per user.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] In a VPC, the previously described mechanism, providing isolation within the cloud, is accompanied with a virtual private network (VPN) function (again, allocated per VPC user) that secures, by means of authentication and encryption, the remote access of the organization to its VPC resources.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] With the introduction of the described isolation levels, an organization using this service is in effect working on a '**virtually private'** cloud (that is, as if the cloud infrastructure is not shared with other users), and hence the name VPC.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] VPC is most commonly used in the context of cloud infrastructure as a service.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] In this context, the infrastructure provider, providing the underlying public cloud infrastructure, and the provider realizing the VPC service over this infrastructure, may be different vendors.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] Amazon Web Services launched Amazon Virtual Private Cloud on 26 August 2009, which allows the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud service to be connected to legacy infrastructure over an IPsec VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] In AWS, the basic VPC is free to use, with users being charged by usage for additional features.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] EC2 and RDS instances running in a VPC can also be purchased using Reserved Instances, however will have a limitation on resources being guaranteed.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] Google Cloud resources can be provisioned, connected, and isolated in a virtual private cloud (VPC) across all Google Cloud regions.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] With Google Cloud, VPCs are global resources and subnets within that VPC are regional resources.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] This allows users to connect zones and regions without the use of additional networking complexity as all data travels, encrypted in transit and at rest, on Google's own global, private network.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] Identity management policies and security rules allow for private access to Google's storage, big data, and analytics managed services.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] VPCs on Google Cloud leverage the security of Google's data centers.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] IBM Cloud launched IBM Cloud VPC on 4 June 2019, provides an ability to manage virtual machine-based compute, storage, and networking resources.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] Pricing for IBM Cloud Virtual Private Cloud is applied separately for internet data transfer, virtual server instances, and block storage used within IBM Cloud VPC.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-cloud] Microsoft Azure offers the possibility of setting up a VPC using Virtual Networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A **virtual private network** (**VPN**) is an overlay network that uses network virtualization to extend a private network across a public network, such as the Internet, via the use of encryption and tunneling protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In a VPN, a tunneling protocol is used to transfer network messages from one network host to another.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Host-to-network VPNs are commonly used by organizations to allow off-site users secure access to an office network over the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs connect two networks, such as an office network and a datacenter.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Provider-provisioned VPNs isolate parts of the provider's own network infrastructure in virtual segments, in ways that make the contents of each segment private with respect to the others.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Individuals also use VPNs to encrypt and attempt to anonymize their network traffic, with VPN services selling access to their own private networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] However, the VPN provider and the online service being accessed via the VPN may have visibility of the user's activities.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful external data sniffing attacks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A network is a group of communicating computers known as hosts, which communicate data to other hosts via communication protocols, as facilitated by networking hardware.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Within a computer network, computers are identified by network addresses, which allow rule-based systems such as Internet Protocol (IP) to locate and identify hosts.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Hosts may also have hostnames, memorable labels for the host nodes, which are rarely changed after initial assignment.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The transmission medium that supports information exchange includes wired media like copper cables, optical fibers, and wireless radio-frequency media.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The arrangement of hosts and hardware within a network architecture is known as the network topology.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A communication protocol is a set of rules for exchanging information over a network.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Communication protocols have various characteristics, such as being connection-oriented or connectionless, or using circuit switching or packet switching.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In a protocol stack, often constructed per the OSI model, communications functions are divided into protocol layers, where each layer leverages the services of the layer below it until the lowest layer controls the hardware that sends information across the media.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The use of protocol layering is ubiquitous across the field of computer networking.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] An important example of a protocol stack is HTTP, the World Wide Web protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] HTTP runs over TCP over IP, the internet protocols, which in turn run over IEEE 802.11, the Wi-Fi protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This stack is used between a wireless router and a personal computer when accessing the web.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Most modern computer networks use protocols based on packet-mode transmission.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A network packet is a formatted unit of data carried by a packet-switched network.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Packets consist of two types of data: control information and user data (payload).
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The control information provides data the network needs to deliver the user data, for example, source and destination network addresses, error detection codes, and sequencing information.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Typically, control information is found in packet headers and trailers, with payload data in between.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The Internet protocol suite, also called TCP/IP, is the foundation of all modern networking and the defining set of protocols for the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] It offers connection-less and connection-oriented services over an inherently unreliable network traversed by datagram transmission using Internet protocol (IP).
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] At its core, the protocol suite defines the addressing, identification, and routing specifications for Internet Protocol Version 4 (IPv4) and for IPv6, the next generation of the protocol with a much enlarged addressing capability.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] VPNs do not make connected users anonymous or unidentifiable to the untrusted medium network provider, such as an Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] However, VPNs can enhance usage privacy by making an ISP unable to access the private data exchanged across the VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Through encryption, VPNs enhance confidentiality and reduce the risk of successful data sniffing attacks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Data packets travelling across a VPN may also be secured by tamper proofing via a message authentication code, prevents the message from being altered or tampered without being rejected, enhancing data integrity.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A number of other implementations exist to ensure authentication of connecting parties.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Tunnel endpoints can be authenticated in various ways during the VPN access initiation, such as by the whitelisting of endpoint IP address.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Authentication may also occur after actual tunnels are already active, for example, with a web captive portal.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Remote-access VPNs may also use passwords, biometrics, two-factor authentication, or other cryptographic methods.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Site-to-site VPNs often use passwords (pre-shared keys) or digital certificates.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling allows a user to access distinct security domains at the same time, using the same or different network connections.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This connection state is usually facilitated through the simultaneous use of a LAN network interface controller (NIC), radio NIC, Wireless LAN NIC, and virtual private network client software application.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Split tunneling is most commonly configured via the use of a remote-access VPN client, which allows the user to simultaneously connect to a nearby wireless network, resources on an off-site corporate network, as well as websites over the Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Advantages of split tunneling include alleviating bottlenecks, conserving bandwidth (as Internet traffic does not have to pass through the VPN server), and enabling a user to not have to continually connect and disconnect when remotely accessing resources..
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Disadvantages include DNS leaks and potentially bypassing gateway-level security that might be in place within the company infrastructure.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Internet service providers often use split tunneling to that implement for DNS hijacking purposes.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A *host-to-network* configuration is analogous to joining one or more computers to a network to which they cannot be directly connected.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This type of extension provides computer access to a local area network of a remote site, or any wider enterprise networks, such as an intranet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Each computer is in charge of activating its own tunnel towards the network it wants to join.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The joined network is only aware of a single remote host for each tunnel.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This may be employed for remote workers, or to enable people accessing their private home or company resources without exposing them on the public Internet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A *site-to-site* configuration connects two networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This configuration expands a network across geographically disparate locations.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Tunneling is only done between gateway devices located at each network location.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] These devices then make the tunnel available to other local network hosts that aim to reach any host on the other side.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This is useful to keep sites connected to each other in a stable manner, like office networks to their headquarters or datacenter.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In this case, any side may be configured to initiate the communication as long as it knows how to reach the other.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In the context of site-to-site configurations, the terms *intranet* and *extranet* are used to describe two different use cases.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] An *intranet* site-to-site VPN describes a configuration where the sites connected by the VPN belong to the same organization, whereas an *extranet* site-to-site VPN joins sites belonging to multiple organizations.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A limitation of traditional VPNs is that they are point-to-point connections and do not tend to support broadcast domains.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Therefore, communication, software, and networking that are based on layer 2 and broadcast packets (such as NetBIOS used in Windows networking) may not be fully supported as on a local area network.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Variants on VPN such as Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) and layer 2 tunneling protocols are designed to overcome this limitation.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Trusted VPNs do not use cryptographic tunneling; instead, they rely on the security of a single provider's network to protect the traffic.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) often overlays trusted VPNs, often with quality-of-service control over a trusted delivery network.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A secure VPN either trusts the underlying delivery network or enforces security with an internal mechanism.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Unless the trusted delivery network runs among physically secure sites only, both trusted and secure models need an authentication mechanism for users to gain access to the VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Mobile VPNs are widely used in public safety where they give law-enforcement officers access to applications such as computer-assisted dispatch and criminal databases, and in other organizations with similar requirements such as field service management and healthcare.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Dynamic Multipoint Virtual Private Network (DMVPN) is a dynamic tunneling form of a virtual private network supported on Cisco IOS-based routers, Huawei AR G3 routers, and Unix-like operating systems.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] DMVPN provides the capability for creating a dynamic-mesh VPN network without having to statically pre-configure all possible tunnel end-point peers, such as IPsec and ISAKMP peers.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] DMVPN is initially configured to build a hub-and-spoke network by statically configuring the hubs (VPN headends) on the spokes; no change in the configuration on the hub is required to accept new spokes.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Using this initial hub-and-spoke network, tunnels between spokes are dynamically built on demand without additional configuration on the hubs or spokes.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This dynamic-mesh capability alleviates the need for any load on the hub to route data between the spoke networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Ethernet VPN (EVPN) is a technology for carrying OSI layer 2 Ethernet traffic as a virtual private network using wide area network protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Multiprotocol Label Switching (MPLS) is a routing technique in telecommunications networks that directs data from one node to the next based on labels rather than network addresses.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Whereas network addresses identify endpoints, MPLS labels identify established paths between endpoints.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] MPLS can encapsulate packets of various network protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In practice, MPLS is mainly used to forward IP protocol data units and Virtual Private LAN Service Ethernet traffic.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Major applications of MPLS are telecommunications traffic engineering and MPLS VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Virtual Private LAN Service (VPLS) is a virtual private network technology that provides Ethernet-based multipoint-to-multipoint communication over IP or MPLS networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] It allows geographically dispersed sites to share an Ethernet broadcast domain by connecting sites (including both servers and clients) through pseudowires.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The technologies that can be used as pseudo-wire can be Ethernet over MPLS, L2TPv3 or even GRE.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] There are two IETF standards-track RFCs (RFC 4761 and RFC 4762) describing VPLS establishment.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In contrast to L2TPv3, which allows only point-to-point OSI layer 2 tunnels, VPLS allows any-to-any (multipoint) connectivity.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A virtual private network is based on a tunneling protocol, and may be combined with other network or application protocols to provide additional security and capabilities.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Internet Protocol Security (IPsec) is a standards-based security protocol, initially developed by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) for IPv6, and was required in all standards-compliant implementations of IPv6 before RFC 6434 made it only a recommendation.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The design of IPSec meets most security goals: availability, integrity, and confidentiality.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] IPsec uses encryption, encapsulating an IP packet inside an IPsec packet.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] De-encapsulation happens at the end of the tunnel, where the original IP packet is decrypted and forwarded to its intended destination.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] IPsec is also often supported by network hardware accelerators, which makes IPsec VPN desirable for low-power scenarios, like always-on remote access VPN configurations.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels are set up by the Internet Key Exchange (IKE) protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] IPsec tunnels made with IKE version 1 (also known as IKEv1 tunnels, or often just "IPsec tunnels") can be used alone to provide VPN but are often combined with the Layer 2 Tunneling Protocol (L2TP) to reuse existing L2TP-related implementations for more flexible authentication features (e.g.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] IKE version 2, which was created by Microsoft and Cisco, can be used alone to provide IPsec VPN functionality.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Its primary advantages are the native support for authenticating via the Extensible Authentication Protocol (EAP) and that the tunnel can be seamlessly restored when the IP address of the associated host is changing, which is typical of a roaming mobile device, whether on 3G or 4G LTE networks.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Transport Layer Security (SSL/TLS) can tunnel an entire network's traffic (as it does in the OpenVPN project and SoftEther VPN project) or secure an individual connection.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A number of vendors provide remote-access VPN capabilities through TLS.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] A VPN based on TLS can connect from locations where the usual TLS web navigation (HTTPS) is supported without requiring additional configuration.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH offers VPN tunneling (distinct from port forwarding) to secure remote connections to a network, inter-network links, and remote systems.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] OpenSSH server provides a limited number of concurrent tunnels.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The VPN feature itself does not support personal authentication.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] SSH is more often used to remotely connect to machines or networks instead of a site to site VPN connection.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] OpenVPN is a free and open-source VPN protocol based on the TLS protocol.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] It supports perfect forward-secrecy, and most modern secure cipher suites, like AES, Serpent, TwoFish, etc.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] It is currently being developed and updated by OpenVPN Inc., a non-profit providing secure VPN technologies.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Secure Socket Tunneling Protocol (SSTP) is a form of VPN tunnel that provides a mechanism to transport Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) traffic through an SSL/TLS channel.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] WireGuard is a protocol designed to be more lightweight than OpenVPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In 2020, WireGuard support was added to both the Linux and Android kernels, opening it up to adoption by VPN providers.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] By default, WireGuard utilizes the Curve25519 protocol for key exchange and ChaCha20-Poly1305 for encryption and message authentication, but also includes the ability to pre-share a symmetric key between the client and server.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Desktop, smartphone and other end-user device operating systems usually support configuring remote access VPN from their graphical or command-line tools.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] However, due to the variety of, often non standard, VPN protocols, there exist many third-party applications that implement additional protocols not yet or no longer natively supported by the OS.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] For instance, Android lacked native IPsec IKEv2 support until version 11, and users needed to install third-party apps in order to connect that kind of VPN.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Conversely, Windows does not natively support plain IPsec IKEv1 remote access native VPN configuration (commonly used by Cisco and Fritz!Box VPN solutions).
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Network appliances, such as firewalls, often include VPN gateway functionality for either remote access or site-to-site configurations.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Their administration interfaces often facilitate setting up virtual private networks with a selection of supported protocols.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In some cases, like in the open source operating systems devoted to firewalls and network devices (like OpenWrt, IPFire, PfSense or OPNsense), it is possible to add support for additional VPN protocols by installing missing software components or third-party apps.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Commercial appliances with VPN features based on proprietary hardware or software platforms usually support a consistent VPN protocol across their products, but do not allow customizations outside the use cases they implement.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] This is often the case for appliances that rely on hardware acceleration of VPNs to provide higher throughput or support a larger number of simultaneously connected users.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] According to a 2022 estimate, 3% of Chinese netizens use VPNs, compared to 8.5% of Americans.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] In China, VPNs are increasingly blocked and unauthorized usage can be subject to fines and legal prosecution.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Based on its estimates of leaked government documents, ChinaFile estimated in 2026 that VPN demand in China was in the low single digits.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] It also estimated that foreign apps blocked by the Great Firewall have extremely low traffic, particularly compared to domestic apps; the top five domestic apps saw traffic that was 1,000 times more than the top five foreign apps.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] As of 2025, approximately 1.75 billion people used VPNs.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] By 2027, this market is projected to grow to $76 billion.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] Amid Internet restrictions and blocking in Russia, Internet activists created the Amnezia VPN project in 2020 during a digital rights hackathon organized by Roskomsvoboda.
[src:aws-vpc/virtual-private-network] The service gained popularity among Russian users by providing access to blocked resources, as well as features aimed at enhancing anonymity and resistance to traffic analysis.
